Section 1:
1 L.D. 156
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 89, L.D. 156, “An Act to Improve
10 Notifications Related to Substance-exposed Infants”
11 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
12 following:
13 'Sec. 1. 22 MRSA §4002, sub-§5-D is enacted to read:
14 5-D. Family care plan. "Family care plan" means a plan of safe care as described in
15 the federal Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act.
16 Sec. 2. 22 MRSA §4004-B, as amended by PL 2019, c. 342, §2, is repealed.
17 Sec. 3. 22 MRSA §4004-C is enacted to read:
18 §4004-C. Infants born affected by substance abuse or withdrawal symptoms resulting
19 from prenatal drug exposure or fetal alcohol spectrum disorder
20 The department shall:
21 1. Receive notifications. Receive notifications from health care providers, or their
22 designees, regarding infants who are identified as having been born affected by substance
23 abuse or having withdrawal symptoms resulting from prenatal drug exposure or who have
24 a fetal alcohol spectrum disorder;
25 2. Develop family care plan. For each infant for whom the department receives a
26 notification under subsection 1, develop, with the assistance of any health care provider
27 involved in the infant's caregiver's or the infant's medical or mental health care, a family
28 care plan, including any appropriate referrals for services for the child or caregiver. This
29 subsection may not be construed as limiting a health care provider's ability to develop a
30 family care plan for any family who could benefit from one;
31 3. Collect data. Collect data for reporting in a manner that complies with the federal
32 Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act;
33 4. Comply with section 4004. For any infant about whom the department receives a
34 report of abuse or neglect, comply with section 4004, subsection 2; and
Page 1 - 132LR0271(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 89, L.D. 156
1 5. Adopt rules. Adopt rules to implement this section. Rules adopted pursuant to this
2 subsection are routine technical rules as defined in Title 5, chapter 375, subchapter 2-A.
3 For the purposes of this section, "health care provider" means a person described in
4 section 4011-A, subsection 1, paragraph A, subparagraphs (1) to (10), (15), (17) to (20)
5 and (22) or any person who assists in the delivery or birth of a child for compensation,
6 including, but not limited to, a midwife.
7 Sec. 4. 22 MRSA §4011-B, as amended by PL 2019, c. 342, §3, is repealed.
8 Sec. 5. 22 MRSA §4011-C is enacted to read:
9 §4011-C. Notification regarding infants affected by substance abuse or withdrawal
10 symptoms resulting from prenatal drug exposure or fetal alcohol spectrum
11 disorder
12 1. Notification regarding infants affected by substance abuse or withdrawal
13 symptoms resulting from prenatal drug exposure or fetal alcohol spectrum disorder.
14 A health care provider involved in the delivery or care of an infant the provider identifies
15 as having been born affected by substance abuse, as having withdrawal symptoms resulting
16 from prenatal drug exposure or as having a fetal alcohol spectrum disorder shall notify the
17 department of that condition in the infant.
18 A. This section, and any notification made pursuant to this section, may not be
19 construed to establish a definition of "abuse" or "neglect."
20 B. This section, and any notification made pursuant to this section, may not be
21 construed to require prosecution for any illegal action, including, but not limited to, the
22 act of exposing a fetus to drugs or other substances.
23 2. Report. When a health care provider suspects that an infant has been abused or
24 neglected, the provider shall report to the department in accordance with section 4011-A,
25 subsection 1, paragraph A. If the infant has a family care plan developed under section
26 4004-C, subsection 2, a copy of the family care plan must accompany the report.
27 3. Definition. For purposes of this section, "health care provider" means a person
28 described in section 4011-A, subsection 1, paragraph A, subparagraphs (1) to (10), (15),
29 (17) to (20) and (22) or any person who assists in the delivery or birth of a child for
30 compensation, including, but not limited to, a midwife.
31 4. Rulemaking. The department shall adopt rules to implement this section. Rules
32 adopted pursuant to this subsection are routine technical rules as defined in Title 5, chapter
33 375, subchapter 2-A.'
34 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
35 number to read consecutively.
36 SUMMARY
3377 This amendment replaces the bill. It establishes and defines a family care plan in
3388 statute as a plan of safe care as described in the federal Child Abuse Prevention and
3399 Treatment Act. It specifies the procedures for health care providers to notify the
4400 Department of Health and Human Services regarding infants affected by substance abuse
4411 or withdrawal symptoms resulting from prenatal drug exposure, including developing a
4422 family care plan. It requires data collection in a manner that complies with federal law.
Page 2 - 132LR0271(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 89, L.D. 156
413 The amendment also strikes the language in the bill that removes references in law to
424 notifications not being construed to establish a definition of "abuse" or "neglect" or to
435 require prosecution. It removes references to investigations by the Department of Health
446 and Human Services upon notification.
457 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
468 (See attached)
Page 3 - 132LR0271(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
